In reviewing data collected and analyzed by Johns Hopkins, the United States has seen 1,083,064 positive COVID cases. Additionally, CDC data suggests that the country has experienced an average of 293,946 cases per week. Using the CDC figure would leave us at 1,175,784 cases in the next week. This same time last year, the United States saw a total of 2,509,456 cases. When you consider the creation and widespread distribution of booster shots, it’s highly unlikely that we see more than 2.25M cases in the next month, which is what led me to assigning fairly low probabilities to events F, G, and H. I assigned relatively low probabilities to events A and B for similar reasons. Lastly, the frequency with which folks are currently testing relative to last year’s frequency is much lower, which will likely lead to fewer reported cases.

Over the past month, COVID-19 cases have totaled approximately 1.1 million cases. Though the number of COVID-19 cases has trended downwards, as the weather gets colder, the number of cases is likely to increase. However, this period excludes cases that may result from the Thanksgiving holiday. Two other factor to consider is that some people will receive COVID-19 boosters in the lead up to the holiday season and with the use of take-home tests, people are less likely to report COVID-19 cases. Therefore, I believe COVID-19 cases will be higher than the month prior, but not by a significant margin.
I first looked at the time frame.

Last month (between September 25th to October 24th), there were approximately 1,172,000 COVID cases in the US according to the CDC. In 2021 there were about 2,513,000 cases between October 24th and November 23th, and 2,549,000 cases between September 29th and October 27th, which suggests that the number of cases should not dramatically increase next month even though the weather is getting colder and people are probably going to be more indoors (which would lead to higher contamination rates). I don’t expect any spike between October 24th and November 23rd except perhaps for the last week as cases from Thanksgiving will begin to show, so I’m adding some weight to answer D.

Unless transmission slows down (unlikely), cases are likely to be in the 1,000,000 to 1,500,000 range. If they speed up, this could spill into the 1,500,000 plus range, though unlikely to cross 3,000,000

The analysis is as follows:

A lot less people are testing and reporting their results than last year so I expect the results to be less than what I originally benchmarked for last year which was greater than 2.5 million. I then considered comparing each weeks reporting to last year. This seems like about half the number of cases are being reported by roughly estimating the amounts. Therefore, I set my benchmark at half of the total number of cases which falls in answer D, and distribute my answers around it.

As of October 26, the current number of weekly cases amounted to 265,000 cases across the United States. While the weekly case load per 100k people is likely to increase in a Covid-typical wave over the coming weeks, the range of expected cases per week is broadly not below 250k and not more than 500k until mid-November. It takes a historical average of 2-3 weeks for Covid infections to double at these numbers. Extrapolating this forward in a simple calculation, I would expect an averaged weekly infection number of ~350k x 4 weeks until the end date of November 23rd. This would yield around 1.4 million cases. Hence, I would argue that option C is the likeliest, with option D receiving the second highest likelihood.

Given that the average number of cases in the last 4 weeks, it’s unlikely that there are fewer than 1,000,000 cases, which is why I’ve assigned lower probabilities for Answer A and B. During the past nine months, the average number of weekly cases in the United States has ranged between a low of 193,000 (March 30 2022) and a high of 924,000 ( July 27 2022). While the peak number of cases occurred in January at 5,589,000, this spike was far outside the normal range over the past two years. Looking at last year's trend, we can see that the rate for the same week in 2021 was 505,000, with a similar dip into October and a rise after November. However, the minimum point in October 2021 was 250k cases higher than this October. Based on these trends and last year's data point, I think there is a high likelihood that the number of COVID cases will stay under 1,000,000, with a slightly higher probability of remaining under 500,000.

Adjusting up my bottom buckets some. 500k requires a daily average of <16k. We're at 26k right now and could very well see 16k, but I don't know that we'll get there fast enough and then have enough days at 6k or lower (we haven't seen a 7 day average under 10k since March 2020). Meanwhile, 1M requires a daily average under 32k, which we're under now and likely to stay under for at least a bit, even if a new wave immediately hits.

The outside view here is either COVID trends over the past two years, or pandemic dynamics from historical analogues. Taking COVID as a relatively distinct historical event, I choose COVID trends over the past two years (with the recognition that vaccines + variants DRAMATICALLY) impact the picture. The delta in this same timeframe between this year and last year is about .5x, so a very simplistic outside view would suggest the number might half once more.

Simply noting that cases would have to grow by average of ~3% per day during this period in order to hit Bin 4. Quite possible, but putting most weight in Bin 3 for now. Fully expect we'll see a surge similar to what has happened in several European countries, which avg. daily cases roughly double between early/mid-Sept and early/mid-Oct, before tapering back off.

Almost 3 years into the pandemic, we are at the point of herd immunity move. Most 7-day and 30-day moving averages also show a perceptible downward trend. Comparing the same period last year with this year would not be reasonable as most people weren't vaccinated at that period in 2021, herd immunity was not achieved, and the delta and omicron variants had not reared their heads. So the sum of new cases during that period cannot serve as a reliable guide to what will happen in the same period this year as there is little evidence of seasonality to COVID 19 (it's not the flu). But that figure of 2,513,325 new cases can still serve as a good sanity check.

There are currently about 261,000 new COVID cases per week. If the rate stays the same, the monthly new number of cases would be 1,044,000. However, I project cases are likely to rise, given the cold weather, which brings people indoors and (according to one article I read) may also affect the inherent virus transmissibility itself. Already, there are a large number of non-COVID viruses increasing (RSV, flu, enterovirus). Based on the history of the typical rate of rise of COVID cases when rates have risen, the rate typically goes up by about 80,000 per week. Over four weeks, compounded, if rates increase this week, that would be an additional 800,000 cases above the level if rates do not rise (1,044,000), bringing the total for the month to about 1.8 million new cases. If an upward trend in case rates doesn’t start for a couple weeks, then the total may be closer to 1.5 million.

Looking at the total of the last month, and knowing that the season for respiratory diseases like the flu (and covid) start, and that many people start hanging out more in closed spaces due to the weather, I think the number will be higher than the previous month.

However, winter is coming and the Atlantic reported a low booster uptake (https://www.theatlantic.com/health/archive/2022/10/americas-covid-booster-rates-are-a-bad-sign-for-winter/671860/).

After discussing with my classmates, I acknowledged that I should account for more variability in my forecasts. On the lower end, I needed to consider the benefits of widespread vaccinations and the possibility that despite positive COVID cases there may be lower reporting due to familiarity with the virus and its effects. On the higher end, I need to account for decreased vigilance in applying COVID protection measures. Therefore, I expanded my distribution.

The average 4-weeks number of new cases in the US since the beginning of the pandemic is 2.78 million. The average for 2022 (excluding the January peak driven by the Omicron variable) was 2.32 million new cases every 4 weeks. The graph shows cyclical trends of Covid cases, and it seems that we are currently at the bottom of the latest curve, which seems to indicate that cases will rise in the following weeks. The rolling 4-weeks new cases in the last month ranged between 1.7 million to 1.1. million cases. Assuming that cases will rise in the next weeks, my guess is that total cases will most likely be somewhere between 1 and 2 million.
We are now at the end of a peak that was in place five weeks ago, so it will be expected for the number of cases to rise significantly at the end of November.

There have been fewer than 500K new cases during the past six weeks. Furthermore, 79% of the population have received at least one vaccine and 68% are fully vaccinated. This could suggest that new cases could remain below the 500K. However, the cold season is coming and there are indications that the virus is more contagious in winter. In the past two winters there have been a significant increase in new cases. Hence, there is higher probability that cases could reach over a million, but would likely remain at under two million (as it was the case in 2020) given the larger share of population already vaccinated and the fact that there may be a large share of unreported cases (as people have learned to live with the virus and may treat it as yet another cold).

Cases are down a downslope trajectory over the last few weeks; last week’s cases numbered 260,000, while the week before was 265,000. However, we are also seeing these numbers slow. Judging from the trajectory, I would expect cases to equal roughly 1 million (although we could see a situation where there’s a spike. Therefore, these numbers seem right to me.

We have had between 40,000 and 50,000 daily cases (weekly average divided by 7) for the last month. Extrapolating that average would suggest something between 1.2 and 1.5 million over the next month. Given increased rates of vaccinations, it seems unlikely that cases will match last fall. Extrapolating based on the most recent average (36,486.86) gives 1,094,605.8 cases over the next 30 days. Fall usually brings an increase in the number of cases and it seems like the US has not yet had its mini-wave of the new variants (e.g., BA.4.6) that recently caused an increase in cases in Europe. As a result, I'm leaning towards 1.1m as a likely lower bound and 2.5m (last year's numbers) as a strict upper bound as I don't expect things to go worse than 2021 (it didn't in Europe).

This is a tough one. We are going to see an uptick moving into the winter months, by how much is hard to say. I think it's pointless to compare it to last year's data because the situation we have now (with regard to vaccination) is not comparable.

First, I discarded the anchor of 2.5m cases over the same period in 2021 because the weekly numbers reflect a different baseline than we’re starting with in 2022. But what is useful from that period are the growth rates of new cases (-5.3%, -0.2%, 6.8%, 14.2%, and 8.9%). This trend suggests that cases will initially decline at a slower rate before increasing as we move from late October into November. Next, I took those rates mentioned above and created growth rate ranges to use in a simulation over 100 potential outcomes. I used the average of the 100 simulations for each week to derive weekly case totals and rolling four-week totals.

We have historically in this pandemic seen a spike of cases starting in late-November into December. We also are likely in a similar state of post-pandemic openness and vaccination status as mid-summer, when new case numbers rose to a high of 924k. I think it will be unlikely that a surge greater than the summer occurs, particularly as more people get vaccinated against new strands and fewer people are testing and report than in the years prior.

Since the current new COVID case count is over 835,000, I zeroed those out. I then looked at the October-November trends in 2020 and 2021, basing it on dates closest to 24 Oct to the 23 Nov, which averaged approximately 4,177,000 (2020: 4,989,000 and 2021: 3,365,000). With this in mind, I weighted Answer F higher than any other option. I weighted Answer E with the second highest probability because I think vaccines will lower the overall new cases and the trend from 2020 to 2021 showed a decrease as well.
